==English==
===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|ȝate}}, {{m|enm|yate}}, {{m|enm|ȝeat}}, alternative forms of {{m|enm|gate}}, {{m|enm|gat}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġeat||a gate, door}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*gatą||hole, opening}}.
====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# {{obsolete form of|en|gate}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=c. 1420|first=Thomas|last=Hoccleve|title=Dialogue|passage=Syn he of helthe hath opned me the '''yate'''}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1579|year2=1679|first=Edmund|last=Spenser|authorlink=Edmund Spenser|title={{w|The Shepheardes Calender}}|chapter=May|title2=The Works of that Famous English Poet, Mr. Edmond Spenser|location2=London|publisher2=Henry Hills|page2=21|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=S9tBAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA2-PA21|passage=For thy my Kiddie, be ruled by me, <br> And never give trust to his trechery: <br> And if he chance come when I am abroad, <br> Spar the '''yate''' fast, for fear of fraud.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1847|year_published=1870|title={{w|Wuthering Heights}}|first=Emily|last=Brontë|authorlink=Emily Bronte|location=London|publisher=Smith, Elder & Co.|page=69|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=7wXy0iWQhmUC&pg=PA69|passage=He's left th' '''yate''' at t' full swing, and Miss's pony has trodden dahn two rigs o' corn , and plottered through, raight o'er into t' meadow!}}
